But the optimized function given is:

```cpp
int StrVec::FindI(const char* s, int startAt) const {
    int sLen = str::Leni(s);
    auto end = this->end();
    for (auto it = this->begin() + startAt; it != end; it++) {
        StrSpan s2 = it.Span();
        if (s2.Len() == sLen && str::EqI(s, s2.CStr())) {
            return it.idx;
        }
    }
    return -1;
}
```

So the optimized version adds a length check before doing the case-insensitive comparison. This is a valid optimization because comparing lengths is cheap and can avoid the more expensive `str::EqI` call when the lengths differ. This maintains correctness because if lengths differ, the strings cannot be equal even with case-insensitivity. It also improves performance by short-circuiting.

However, note that the original function had a TODO comment about checking length first. So the optimized version implements that TODO. The optimization is valid and correct.

But we must also consider that the optimized function is a drop-in replacement. It has the same signature and behavior, except it adds an extra length check. This does not change the output, only makes it faster in cases where lengths differ.

Therefore, the optimized function is a valid optimization.